issue(id="0005" status="open")
  title Refactor scrubs sandbox policy toward Nushell and declarative artifacts
  user-story
    as-a scrubs maintainer evolving the dirty-runtime system
    i-want the sandbox policy layer to be more declarative and more naturally authored in Nushell where practical
    so-that the current working shell-heavy implementation can become easier to inspect, override, and maintain without destabilizing bootstrap-time safety
  premise.
    The current scrubs dirty-runtime implementation is working well, but it now
    relies on a meaningful amount of shell code. That is acceptable for the
    bootstrap path where `/bin/sh` remains the safest contract, yet some of the
    current shell surface is really policy or data rather than inherently
    POSIX-only logic. In particular, the guest-wide sandbox definition is a
    declared artifact conceptually, but today it is still expressed as sourced
    shell arrays and helper variables because the launcher and installer
    consume it directly.

    A cleaner long-term shape would preserve POSIX shell for the narrow parts
    of scrubs that truly need to run before Nushell can be assumed, while
    moving the sandbox policy layer toward a more declarative artifact that can
    be authored or generated with Nushell. That would improve operator
    visibility, make project-shim overrides easier to reason about, and reduce
    the amount of imperative shell used for policy expression without forcing a
    risky all-at-once rewrite of the runtime launcher.
  acceptance-criteria
    criterion Scrubs has a documented split between bootstrap-time code that should remain POSIX shell and runtime policy that is a candidate for Nushell or another declarative representation.
    criterion The guest sandbox definition is no longer coupled exclusively to sourced shell arrays, and there is a clearer artifact boundary for helper commands, copied files, read-only binds, writable paths, and ambient Linux facts.
    criterion Project shims can continue to provide guest-specific sandbox overrides through the resulting artifact model without becoming more fragile than the current shell-based override path.
    criterion Any migration path preserves the current working dirty-runtime behavior, including proxy-shim generation, helper-root assembly, and repeat bootstrap survivability.
    criterion The work explicitly avoids rewriting bootstrap-critical scripts into Nushell unless the new contract is shown to be at least as reliable in early-boot and recovery scenarios.
  review-items
    item(status="completed").
      Decide whether the best intermediate form is Nushell-authored data,
      generated shell artifacts, a plain data file format, or some combination
      of those approaches. Current direction: `sandbox-policy.nuon` is the
      source artifact, and scrubs renders guest-local shell definitions from it
      for the existing launcher and fallback paths. Project shims now override
      policy through `sandbox-policy.nuon` only, and legacy
      `sandbox-definition.sh` shim overrides have been removed after disposable
      non-Tailscale guest bootstrap and re-bootstrap validation.
    item(status="completed").
      Identify whether `install-dirty-tools.sh` should migrate before
      `dirty-exec.sh`, since the policy layer likely offers better leverage
      than a full launcher rewrite. Current direction: the installer and policy
      rendering now share a Nu module, while `dirty-exec.sh` remains shell for
      now.
    item(status="open").
      Keep `guest-apply.sh` and the seed installer under explicit scrutiny
      before attempting any Nushell migration there; they likely remain better
      served by POSIX shell for the foreseeable future.
